[{"link":"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege","name":"Denis Mukwege","year":2018,"category":"Peace","country":"Congo, Democratic Republic","text":"Denis Mukwege , Peace, 2018","date_of_birth":"1955-03-30T00:00:00.000","date_of_death":null,"place_of_birth":"Bukavu","place_of_death":null,"gender":"male","award_age":63,"born_in":null,"mini_bio":"<p><b>Denis Mukwege<\/b> (<span class=\"rt-commentedText nowrap\"><span class=\"IPA nopopups noexcerpt\" lang=\"en-fonipa\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Help:IPA\/English\" title=\"Help:IPA\/English\">\/<span style=\"border-bottom:1px dotted\"><span title=\"'m' in 'my'\">m<\/span><span title=\"\/\u028a\/: 'u' in 'push'\">\u028a<\/span><span title=\"'k' in 'kind'\">k<\/span><span title=\"\/\u02c8\/: primary stress follows\">\u02c8<\/span><span title=\"'w' in 'wind'\">w<\/span><span title=\"\/e\u026a\/: 'a' in 'face'\">e\u026a<\/span><span title=\"\/\u0261\/: 'g' in 'guy'\">\u0261<\/span><span title=\"\/i\/: 'y' in 'happy'\">i<\/span><\/span>\/<\/a><\/span><\/span>;<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-1\">[1]<\/a><\/sup> born 1 March 1955)<sup id=\"cite_ref-eu141021_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-eu141021-2\">[2]<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-fondationchirac131010_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-fondationchirac131010-3\">[3]<\/a><\/sup> is a Congolese <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Gynecologist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gynecologist\">gynecologist<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-4\">[4]<\/a><\/sup> and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Pentecostal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pentecostal\">Pentecostal<\/a> <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Pastor\" title=\"Pastor\">pastor<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-religionnews.com_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-religionnews.com-5\">[5]<\/a><\/sup> He founded and works in <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Panzi_Hospital\" title=\"Panzi Hospital\">Panzi Hospital<\/a> in <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Bukavu\" title=\"Bukavu\">Bukavu<\/a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-religionnews.com_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-religionnews.com-5\">[5]<\/a><\/sup> where he specializes in the treatment of women who have been <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Sexual_violence_in_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo\" title=\"Sexual violence in the Democratic Republic of the Congo\">raped by armed rebels<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-:0-6\">[6]<\/a><\/sup> In 2018, Mukwege and Iraqi Yazidi human rights activist <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Nadia_Murad\" title=\"Nadia Murad\">Nadia Murad<\/a> were jointly awarded the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize<\/a> for \"their efforts to end <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Wartime_sexual_violence\" title=\"Wartime sexual violence\">the use of sexual violence as a weapon of war and armed conflict<\/a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-7\">[7]<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-8\">[8]<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>Mukwege's continued demand for justice for the victims of the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Congo_conflicts\" class=\"mw-redirect mw-disambig\" title=\"Congo conflicts\">Congo conflicts<\/a> has resulted in him receiving threats against his life and the Panzi hospital. He has received these death threats on social media platforms, which emerged from various sources including Mukwege's country of origin, the DRC, and adjoining countries, namely <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Rwanda\" title=\"Rwanda\">Rwanda<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Uganda\" title=\"Uganda\">Uganda<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-9\">[9]<\/a><\/sup> Reportedly, the threats have emerged following Denis' increasing calls for perpetrators who were named in a decade-old <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/United_Nations\" title=\"United Nations\">UN<\/a> report, to be brought before an international tribunal.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-10\">[10]<\/a><\/sup> A previous <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Assassination\" title=\"Assassination\">assassination<\/a> attempt was made on Mukwege's life in 2012, which resulted in him and his family leaving the country over concerns for their safety.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-11\">[11]<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>Mukwege has treated thousands of women who were victims of rape as a weapon of war since the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Second_Congo_War\" title=\"Second Congo War\">Second Congo War<\/a>, some of them more than once, performing up to ten operations a day during his 17-hour working days.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-:0-6\">[6]<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Dr._Denis_Mukwege_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-Dr._Denis_Mukwege-12\">[12]<\/a><\/sup> According to <i><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/The_Globe_and_Mail\" title=\"The Globe and Mail\">The Globe and Mail<\/a><\/i>, Mukwege is \"likely the world's leading expert on repairing injuries of rape\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nolen_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-Nolen-13\">[13]<\/a><\/sup> In 2013, he was awarded the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Right_Livelihood_Award\" title=\"Right Livelihood Award\">Right Livelihood Award<\/a> for \"his courageous work healing women survivors of war-time sexual violence and speaking up about its root causes.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-14\">[14]<\/a><\/sup> Dr. Mukwege's efforts to bring international<sup id=\"cite_ref-dictionary.com_15-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-dictionary.com-15\">[15]<\/a><\/sup> attention to the prevalent use of sexual violence as a weapon of war in the Democratic Republic of Congo and his demands for the perpetrators to be brought to justice has resulted in him becoming a renowned <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Activism\" title=\"Activism\">activist<\/a> for <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Human_rights\" title=\"Human rights\">human rights<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\"\/Gender_equality\" title=\"Gender equality\">gender equality<\/a> both within the DRC and internationally.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Dr._Denis_Mukwege_12-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Denis_Mukwege#\"cite_note-Dr._Denis_Mukwege-12\">[12]<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p>","bio_image":"full\/672e1f4878fcd113a5130a7ca06bf6379b0c6a57.jpg"}]